-- 
German Stocks Fall; Deutsche Bank, Commerzbank Drop, Deutsche Boerse Gains

-- B y   P e t e r   L e v r i n g
-- 
2011-05-16T16:04:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-16/german-shares-slide-as-greece-calls-for-increased-eu-bailout.html
German shares fell for a fourth day
as  Greece  asked European Union member states and the
 International Monetary Fund  for a bigger bailout.  Commerzbank AG slipped 3.5 percent after WestLB AG cut its
rating on  Germany ’s second-largest lender.  Deutsche Boerse AG (DB1) ,
which is seeking to acquire NYSE Euronext, surged 3.8 percent as
rival bidders withdrew their offer after talks with the  U.S.
Department of Justice  made “clear” that they would fail to
secure regulatory approval.  The DAX dropped 15.77, or 0.2 percent, to 7,387.54 at the
5:30 p.m. close in  Frankfurt . The measure has fallen 1.5 percent
over the last four days. The broader  HDAX Index (HDAX)  lost 0.3
percent.  “The Greek ghost is out spooking investors, but the market
is also looking for direction after the earnings season,”
Henrik Henriksen, chief of strategy at Copenhagen-based PFA
Pension A/S, said today in a phone interview.  Euro-area countries, led by Germany, may grant Greece extra
aid or more time to pay back official loans in exchange for
deeper budget cuts. EU finance ministers met in Brussels today
to consider whether to boost the Mediterranean country’s 110
billion-euro ($156 billion) bailout. They also considered
whether to make bondholders share the costs.  Commerzbank AG (CBK)  fell 3.5 percent to 3.85 euros. WestLB cut
its recommendation on the Frankfurt-based lender to “sell”
from “reduce.”  Deutsche Bank AG (DBK) , Germany’s biggest lender,
slumped 0.8 percent to 41.90 euros. The European Stoxx 600 Banks
Index fell 0.4 percent.  Volkswagen, BMW, Daimler  Volkswagen slid 0.8 percent to 127.45 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI) 
lost 0.9 percent to 50.09 euros after the maker of Mercedes
trucks and luxury cars increased its joint bid with Rolls-Royce
Group Plc for engine maker  Tognum AG. (TGM)  Daimler and Rolls-Royce
increased their offer by 8.3 percent, submitting a 2.4 billion-
euro bid.  RWE AG (RWE)  dropped 1.6 percent to 42.22 euros after Germany’s
opposition Social Democrats said they want to cut the market
share of the country’s four biggest electricity utilities to
less than 50 percent from more than 80 percent within 10 years.  Deutsche Boerse  soared 3.8 percent to 56.40 euros after
Nasdaq OMX Group Inc. and IntercontinentalExchange Inc. withdrew
their proposal to buy NYSE Euronext. In February, Deutsche
Boerse agreed to buy the operator of the New York Stock
Exchange.  Germany’s largest builder  Hochtief AG (HOT)  rose 1.7 percent to
58.47 euros after posting a first-quarter loss of 169.5 million
euros. Equinet Bank AG increased its rating on the shares to
“buy” from “accumulate.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Peter Levring in Copenhagen at 
 plevring1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Andrew Rummer at 
